paragraphs.title: Exploring the Data
paragraphs.text:
%md

This is an IoT demo. Power Transformers generate one report every minute. Each report brings many features such as Transformer Load, Vibration, TopOilTemperature, etc.

It is up to us to interpret a transformer report and detect that it is about to fail before it does. There is a *threat* level that was created based on past reports of failures.

Transformers may fail because of many reasons. For instance, any transformer, indepedently of its vendor, if submitted to a load that it can't handle will overheat and it's threat level will increase from 0 to 1 and continue increasing up to 5 (if it doesn't explodes before it!).

We can observe this by using Zeppelin's basic data exploration features and the data we have collected on IRIS from all transformers:

paragraphs.title: Anomaly Detection
paragraphs.text:
%md

This is an easy relationship between Power Load and Oil Temperature. But some times a transformer will start failing unexpectedly. How can we detect that a transformer is behaving out of its normal parameters without generating false positives or, worse, false negatives?

Some transformers from the same vendor may be operating under the sun, while others may be under ground. A bird nest may cause some short circuit, trees, rain or snow may interfere as well.

That is what we call "anomalies". To detect that an anomaly is happening, we must first get to know our transformers! So instead of treating all transformers from a vendor as if they were all the same, we must treat their signals as if they where from totally different vendors. Each transformer has its own personality!
